```
CREATE TABLE nist80053_controls (
  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
  family TEXT,
  control_id TEXT,
  control_name TEXT,
  baseline TEXT,
  priority TEXT,
  cia TEXT,
  control_description TEXT,
  control_origination TEXT,
  control_lifecycle_status TEXT,
  control_selection TEXT,
  implementation_status TEXT,
  implementation_detail TEXT,
  implementation_instructions TEXT,
  objective TEXT,
  supplemental_guidance TEXT,
  control_enhancements_by_level TEXT,
  control_relationships TEXT,
  references TEXT,
  disaster_recovery TEXT,
  testing_procedures TEXT,
  assessment_procedures TEXT,
  remediation_guidance TEXT,
  low TEXT,
  moderate TEXT,
  high TEXT,
  critical TEXT,
  family_code TEXT,
  security_tier TEXT
);

COPY nist80053_controls (family, control_id, control_name, baseline, priority, cia, control_description, control_origination,
    control_lifecycle_status, control_selection, implementation_status, implementation_detail, implementation_instructions,
    objective, supplemental_guidance, control_enhancements_by_level, control_relationships, references, disaster_recovery,
    testing_procedures, assessment_procedures, remediation_guidance, low, moderate, high, critical, family_code, security_tier)
FROM '/path/to/nist80053_controls.csv' DELIMITER ',' CSV HEADER;
```

Note: you'll need to replace `/path/to/nist80053_controls.csv` with the actual file path for your NIST 800-53 controls data. This SQL code assumes that you have a CSV file with columns matching the field names specified in this code. The `COPY` statement will insert the data from the CSV file into your `nist80053_controls` table.
